Set up

The main tool weâll be working with in this tutorial is the raster package, so go ahead and install/load that. You can work with rasters using the sp package by loading the raster as a SpatialGridDataFrames, but the raster package is much better, so weâll focus on that! Iâll also mention the new velox package, which is great for big raster datasets at the end of this tutorial.

library(raster)

Raster 101

Raindrops on roses and rasters of land useâ¦ these are a few of my favorite things. Rasters are fantastic tools to store massive amounts of massively cool data. Think of a raster as a matrixâ¦ or a grid of numbers. Each pixel in the raster has number associated with it that tells us something about the data of interest, i.e.

  • How red is this pixel?
  • How near-infrared is this pixel (yes we can answer this)?
  • How wet is this pixel?
  • What grows in this pixel?
  • How deep is the groundwater under this pixel (see GRACE satellite)?
  • How many people live in this pixel (yes, people have done this using night light data)?
  • How many cars are in that parking lot by your house? How many lawn chairs in your backyard (freaking out yet?)? You get the idea.

Let me pause here and state that you are very lucky because you have insanely easy access to incredible, beautiful visualizations of our precious planet.. in near real time, all the time, anywhere. Take a second to ponder that. Then go download Google Earth and start playing.

Get to know your raster

The data stored in rasters can be continuous (precipitation, elevation, reflectance) or categorical (land use category). In this tutorial weâll work with both. For a raster to be a raster, we need a few key pieces of information:

  • Resolution (in space and time!)
  • Extent
  • Values (elevation, land use category, etc.)
  • Projection information

When youâre working with raster data, especially satellite imagery, think carefully about trade-offs between resolution in space and time. Some datasets are available daily at a low spatial resolution; others are available monthly at a high spatial resolution; and others are high spatial and temporal resolution, but massively large and hard for you to work with on your laptop.

The raster package

The raster package includes several raster classes:

  • A RasterLayer contains a single-layer raster. This object contains the number of columns and rows in the raster, the spatial extent, pixel values, and the projection information (stored in CRS format)
  • RasterBricks, and RasterStacks are great for multiband data (i.e.Â multiple spectral bands, observations through time). The main difference is that a RasterBrick can be linked to only one (though multi-layer) file. RasterStacks can be made with multiple files (band from one file merged with a band from another file) - though these objects have to have the same extent and resolution.

In this tutorial, we will focus on learning how to load and manipulate the most commonly used types of raster data. There are tons of raster extensions out there: .grd, .asc, .sdat, .rst, .nc, .tif, .envi, .bil, .img, .hdf. Iâve encountered all of these at some pointâ¦ and the raster package can handle just about all of them. You can find the full list in the raster package documentation.1

Weâll get to bricks later in the tutorial. For now, letâs work with a single layer of my current favorite raster dataset, the CropScape dataset.. This is a categorical raster that covers most of the country from 2000 to present at a 30 meter - YES T-H-I-R-T-Y meter - resolution. Since the dataset was built by the folks at the U.S. Department of Agriculture, there are more detailed categorizations for agricultural lands than for ecosystems.2

I went to the CropScape website and downloaded data for Dekalb County, GA in 2019. To do this, go to the website, click on the little USA map at the top of the page, select County, find Dekalb County, then click Submit. The map should zoom to Dekalb Valley. Next, click the little folder icon with a green arrow on it. Select 2019, Submit and the data should download to your computer. Youâll have to unzip the files and move both files to a local data folder. So I did all that, and can load my raster with the easiest function ever:

cdl <- raster("./data/CDL_2019_13089.tif")
plot(cdl)

Oh wow thatâs pretty. The value of each pixel is indicative of the land use in that pixel (i.e.Â 1 = CORN, etc). You can download the metadata here). The data we downloaded is a GeoTiff, which raster handles seamlessly. Our new cdl object is a RasterLayer object. Whatâs stored in this object? We have extent and dimensions:

cdl@extent
## class      : Extent 
## xmin       : 1066215 
## xmax       : 1098735 
## ymin       : 1240275 
## ymax       : 1277295
print(paste("This groovy data has", cdl@ncols, "columns.", sep = " "))
## [1] "This groovy data has 1084 columns."
print(paste("This groovy data has", cdl@nrows, "rows.", sep = " "))
## [1] "This groovy data has 1234 rows."

Or we can simply call:

dim(cdl)
## [1] 1234 1084    1

We can also find the resolution of our data:

res(cdl)
## [1] 30 30

30 meters!!!!!!!!!!!! Can you believe it!? Go, science, go!!!!

Thereâs also the projection information (cdl@crs) and the data itself (cdl@data). The nice thing about raster objects is that you donât need to specify the @data piece for a number of useful functions to work. Need the max and min values of the raster?

maxValue(cdl)
## [1] 255
minValue(cdl)
## [1] 0

Letâs see a histogram of our pixel values:

hist(cdl)

Lots of low valuesâ¦ possibly some zeros?

length(cdl[cdl == 0])
## [1] 558401

Lots of zeros! What percent of pixels are zero?

length(cdl[cdl == 0])/(cdl@ncols*cdl@nrows)
## [1] 0.4174474

Ooohh 41 percent? This likely means a value of zero indicates missing data. Look at the plot of our raster. Raster datasets are stored with a well defined bounding box, so they are always rectangular. The region of interest, however, is rarely rectangular (unless youâre in one of those states with a bunch of square counties). This leads to a lot of missing data around the edges. Check for this and be wary of missing data when you compute summary stats on your rasterâ¦ You can quickly check to see the value of this âblack spaceâ in the raster plot by indexing pixels at the corners of the raster, i.e.:

cdl[1,1]
##   
## 0

This returns the value of the pixel at location row = 1, column = 1. You can also use the NAvalue() function to identify how NA is coded in a particular dataset:

NAvalue(cdl)
## [1] -Inf

In our case, we donât have a stored NAvalue. You can also use the NAvalue() function to assign a missing value, for example NAvalue(cdl) <- 999.

Back to the high level of zeros in the dataset. Zero isnât NAâ¦ NA implies that there is NO value at a particular pixel. Here, we DO have a value, and that value is zero. If you see an odd value in your dataset, like the zero in this case, itâs a good idea to go to the metadata for the dataset youâre working with to figure out what the strange value indicates. I know from looking at the CropScape metadata that 0 is, in fact, CropScapeâs way of flagging missing data (in this case, data outside of the boundaries of our county). Itâs important to tell R that all pixels with value zero are in fact NA - this way when we do things like compute different statistics on the raster data, the zeros wonât be included. Whew, all that to say, letâs set our zero pixels to NA!

cdl[cdl == 0] <- NA
minValue(cdl)
## [1] 1
maxValue(cdl)
## [1] 242
cdl[1,1]
## [1] NA

Another nice trick to help you check the contents of your raster: you can use the freq() function to build a frequency table for your data. Probably only do this for categorical data, or youâll have a gigantic frequency table:

You can use your plotting skillz to turn this into a ggplot:

library(tidyverse)

  geom_bar(aes(x = reorder(value, desc(count)), y = count), stat = "identity") +
  xlab("Land use category") + ylab("Count of pixels") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  ggtitle("What's going on in our county?")

Raster reprojection

Oftentimes two raster datasets will not line up because of differences in resolution and/or extent. The projectRaster() function from the raster package lets us reproject datasets so they can talk to one another. Letâs look at the projection info for our cdl raster:

cdl@crs
## CRS arguments:
##  +proj=aea +lat_0=23 +lon_0=-96 +lat_1=29.5 +lat_2=45.5 +x_0=0 +y_0=0
## +ellps=GRS80 +towgs84=0,0,0,0,0,0,0 +units=m +no_defs

This is stored in CRS format, which now you guys know all about. Letâs say we want to transform our raster from its current Albers Equal Area projection to a US National Atlas Equal Area projection:

crs <- '+proj=utm +zone=11 +ellps=GRS80 +datum=NAD83 +units=m +no_defs'
cdl_prj <- projectRaster(cdl, res = res(cdl), crs = crs, method = "ngb") # takes a sec
cdl_prj@crs

Note that this can take awhile depending on the size of your raster. Also, BE SURE to think about whether your data is categorical or continuous before you begin reprojecting. Reprojecting rasters means that the cell centroids and even size may change. To assign values to the new cells in the reprojected raster, projectRaster() may have to compute new values for the reprojected cells using one of two interpolation procedures: nearest neighbor (ngb) or bilinear (bilinear) which is the default. If you apply bilinear interpolation to a categorical raster with integer values like 1, 22, 33, 4 etc, youâll end up with pixels with values of averages of these categories (11.5, 27.5). This totally destroys your categorization. So when youâre working with categorical rasters like the CropScape data, be sure you set method = "ngb" in your reprojection.

Another common raster problem is resolution mis-match. What happens if youâve got a 30 meter resolution and a 1 kilometer resolution raster that you want to have talk to each other through raster math? So my bigtimeruleofthumb for mixed resolution data is that you HAVE TO go with the coarser resolution data when you resampleâ¦ if you resample data to a higher resolution, youâre lying to yourself and pretending that you have better data than you actually have. You donât have two 30 meter datasets. You have one awesome 30 meter dataset and one less-than-awesome 1 km dataset. If you want to interact the two, then you really have two 1 km datasets. Bummer, huh? But itâs honest.

Say we want to compute the most common land use category in a 1 kilometer grid. Our cdl dataset is a 30 meter dataset. We can fit 33.3333333 30 meter pixels along the edge of a single 1 kilometer pixel.

cdl_1k <- aggregate(cdl, fact = 33.3333, fun = modal, na.rm=T)
res(cdl_1k)
## [1] 990 990

aggregate() is a cool function that lets you coarsen the resolution of your raster. Here we essentially move from a 30 meter dataset to a 30*30 meter pixel (approximately 1 km). The scaling factor is set as fact. Pixel values in the new raster are determined by a function of your choosing (fun). In our case, we compute the mode landuse and assign that value to our new raster.

What if you donât want a 990 meter resolution dataset? What if you need something thatâs exactly 1000 meters (1 km)? resample() can help:

ideal_ras <- raster(ncol = 55, nrow = 75)
extent(ideal_ras) <- extent(cdl_1k)
res(ideal_ras) <- c(1000,1000)
cdl_1k_2 <- resample(cdl_1k, ideal_ras, method = "ngb")
res(cdl_1k_2)
## [1] 1000 1000

resample() is even easier if you have a raster in the projection/extent you desire. Say that raster is called ideal_rasâ¦ then you simple call resample(current_ras, ideal_ras, method = "ngb"). This is also a way to do subtle shifts in rasters, like shifting centroids.

Other useful functions for moving your raster around:

  • shift() performs linear shifts of your raster
  • rotate() - you guessed it - rotates your raster
  • flip() reverses the order of your raster (x,y to y,x)

Raster math

If you want to find the difference between values in two rasters, itâs fairly complicated:

diff <- raster_1 - raster_1

Donât forget that a raster is just a matrix, so math is a breeze! Well, kindaâ¦ raster math thatâs this simple only works if your rasters have the same extent and resolution and if the calculations are fairly simple. When datasets donât match or youâre interested in complicated functions, the overlay() function is your friend. overlay() takes two or more rasters and applies the same function to them in a way thatâs a bit more efficient than raster math or for-looping. If you get to a place where you think youâll need overlay() let me know. Otherwise, know that the syntax goes a little something like this:

out <- overlay(raster_1, raster_2, function = mySpecialFunction)

Itâs a good tool to know about, just in case. If your dataset is stacked or bricked, youâll want to use calc() instead of overlay() (see below).

If you want to compute some statistic on the entire raster, use cellStats():

ras_mean <- cellStats(raster_1, stat = "mean", na.rm=T) # returns mean of ALL values in the raster

In this case, you could also just extract values from the raster and perform the operation on the extracted values:

ras_mean <- mean(getValues(raster_1))

Math across multi-band rasters

calc() is a useful function to know about. Say you have a raster brick (latitude by longitude by time) with observations of landuse from 2008 to 2015 and you want to compute the most frequent category of land use through time. This is fairly simple:

calc(my_brick, fun = modal, na.rm = T)

Here calc() basically extracts a vector of observations (through time in this case) for each pixel and applies the function specified in fun to each vector.

Another nice function is stackApply(). You can use this to apply a function to a subset of rasters in a raster brick. You just have to provide the indices (i.e.Â index locations along the third dimension) of the rasters of interest, for example:

stackApply(my_brick, fun = modal, indices = c(1, 1, 1, 2, 2, 2), na.rm = T)

In this case, if our my_brick object has six bands, our indexing approach tells stackApply() to compute the mode of the first three layers and the second three layers. Useful!

More on raster math here and here.

Changing raster values

You can index a raster just like a matrix. If, for whatever reason, we want to change all pixels in our cdl_1k raster with a value of 4 to 938, we can do that using simple base R indexing:

cdl_1k[cdl_1k == 4] <- 938

Say you want to do this reclassification for many categories. Then youâll need to use the reclassify() function. To use this function, youâll have to use a sort of âtranslationâ matrix that tells R which values you want to reclassify. For example, if you want to classify values from 1 to 5 as 333, then youâd need to do the following:

new_cdl <- reclassify(cdl_1k, c(1, 5, 333))

Cropping and masking with a shapefile

Cropping rasters in R is pretty straightforward. If you know the coordinates of your new raster extent, then:

new.extent <- extent(c(-125, -100, 20, 50))
out <- crop(raster, new.extent)

You can get the new.extent values from an existing raster by calling extent(new_extent_raster). You can also pull this info out of a shapefile, but youâll have to slightly tweak the format of the extent by forcing it into a matrix format using matrix():

extent <- matrix(st_bbox(new_extent_shapefile), nrow=2)

If you want to crop to a specific shape rather than the extent of that shape, then you need to add an additional step. Say we want to extract the part of this land use raster located in the city of Decatur3 (note that these two spatial datasets have to be in the same projection for the crop() to work):

shp <- readRDS("./data/decatur.RDS")
shp <- spTransform(shp, cdl@crs)
plot(cdl)

plot(shp, add=T)

city_raster <- crop(cdl, shp)
spplot(city_raster)

Notice that this only cropped the land use raster to the extent of the Decatur shapefile, not to the actual boundaries of the shapefile. To do that, we have to add one more step:

city_clean <- mask(city_raster, mask = shp)
plot(city_clean)

Masking by data values

Masking raster data is something we need to do quite a bit in the remote sensing world. We can do this using the mask() function. Letâs say we want to mask pixels classified as âDeveloped - High Intensityâ (124) in our new city raster:

mcity <- mask(cdl, cdl == 124, maskvalue=F)
plot(mcity)

Here maskvalue=F masks all pixels that are NOT classified as shrubland - not much since weâre looking at a highly urban area. If we set this to T, we can mask all pixels classified as alfalfa:

mcity <- mask(cdl, cdl == 124, maskvalue=T)
plot(mcity)

If you want to mask multiple values, just add a list:

multi_mask <- mask(cdl, cdl %in% c(121, 122, 123, 124), maskvalue=T)
plot(multi_mask)

A few extra notes about multi-band rasters

Say you have a Landsat image for the Berkane Region of Morocco:

ls <- brick("./data/maroc.tif")
plot(ls)

The gross lines are because of an error in the Landsat 7 satellite, which you can read more about here. Notice that instead of loading the data with the raster() function, which is great for single-band data, here I use brick() because this data is multi-band. Remember that the main difference between a brick and a stack is that a RasterBrick can be linked to only one (though multi-layer) file, in our case maroc.tif. RasterStacks can be made with multiple files (band from one file merged with a band from another file) - though these objects have to have the same extent and resolution. So if we happened to have our Landsat bands in separate .tif files, weâd want to load the data using stack(). Letâs inspect this data:

dim(ls)  # row, column, band
## [1] 1159 1603    3
summary(ls)
##         maroc.1 maroc.2 maroc.3
## Min.        327     363     438
## 1st Qu.    2259    1205     995
## Median     2536    1632    1230
## 3rd Qu.    2809    1949    1443
## Max.       4755    3858    3390
## NA's     122118  122118  122118

Most of the functions in the raster package that weâve used on single-band rasters also work on multi-band rasters, they just spit out a result for each band in the raster.

minValue(ls)
## [1] 296 339 411
maxValue(ls)
## [1] 4858 4089 3647

We can index the third dimension in these rasters as follows:

# these scripts both pull out the first band and dump it into a new variable called b1
b1 <- ls[,,1]
# or #
b1 <- ls[[1]] # note the double brackets

The two commas in the first command just tells R to select ALL rows and all columns, then only the first band of the multi-band object.

Saving rasters

You can write out a raster using the writeRaster() function in the raster package.

writeRaster(my_raster, "my/directory/raster.tif") # you can use whatever extension you like - I prefer .tif

Finding rasters

USGS data repositories allow you to search for data by time, year, satellite, resolution, etc.:

  • USGS Earth Explorer is what I tend to use, but thereâs alsoâ¦
  • USGS Glovis

You can also download data directly from NASA (easiest when downloading large time-series). University of Maryland maintains a database of pre-processed images for the remote sensing of land surface processes. You can find lots of DEMs here (ASTER and STRM are the most widely used). You can find cool, free high-resolution topographic and bathymetric data here. This website groups data sources by application (e.g.Â oceanography, land surface processes, forecasting) and can be helpful to explore.

BIG rasters

Why bother learning about the velox package when the raster package can essentially handle all of your raster-needs? Well, raster datasets can quickly fall into the realm of âbig data.â Even performing simple tasks on big datasets can involve some computational wizardry. velox singificantly increases the speed of common raster tasks:

Image taken from this post.

velox4 works with both sp and sf objects. Itâs limited in what it can do, but extremely (unbelievably) fast at the subset of common raster tasks it can handle. Take our cdl datasetâ¦ to use velox you have to load your dataset using the velox() command rather than the raster() command:

library(velox) #don't forget to install and load the velox package
cdl <- velox("./data/CDL_2019_13089.tif")
class(cdl)
## [1] "VeloxRaster"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "velox"

cdl is not a raster object, it is a velox object that behaves differently. If you type cdl$ in the console, you can see the list of cool functions you can apply to this object. For example:

cdl$crs
## [1] "+proj=aea +lat_0=23 +lon_0=-96 +lat_1=29.5 +lat_2=45.5 +x_0=0 +y_0=0 +ellps=GRS80 +towgs84=0,0,0,0,0,0,0 +units=m +no_defs"
cdl$extent
## [1] 1066215 1098735 1240275 1277295

Note that you can have a raster dataset that is TOO big to be held in memory by velox() and transformed into a more efficient veloxed-rasterâ¦ Iâve encountered this problem in my work and decided the easiest thing to do was to split my big raster into smaller parts that could be handled by velox, run analyses on these smaller parts, then merge the results back together.

velox objects are mutable, so if you perform an operation on a raster, i.e.Â vx$crop, the velox object is permanently modified by the operation. If you want to keep a copy of the original velox object, you have to make a copy:

cdl_copy <- cdl$copy()

Hereâs some of the basic things that you can do with the velox package, which weâll perform on the cdl_copy object to preserve our original data. Say you want to extract the values of the CropScape dataset in the polygon for Decatur. With raster this takes a lot of time, but not with velox:

# this step reprojected nl to the projection of cdl - it's always faster to reproject a shp rather than a raster
city_values <- cdl$extract(shp)
head(city_values[[1]]) # returned as a list
##      [,1]
## [1,]  141
## [2,]  121
## [3,]  141
## [4,]  142
## [5,]  141
## [6,]  141

Whatâs really cool here is that you can add any function to the extract() function to apply a function the the extracted data:

city_mean <- cdl$extract(shp, fun = function(x) mean(x, na.rm=T))
city_mean
##       [,1]
## 0 125.5796

You can also crop data using shapefiles (or extent information):

cdl_copy$extent
## [1] 1066215 1098735 1240275 1277295
cdl_copy$crop(shp) # crop to boundary
cdl_copy$extent
##   res.x columns    rows   res.y 
## 1071795 1075635 1253265 1258125

We can also perform quick aggregations on velox objects (remember, once performed on cdl_copy the change is permanent):

cdl_copy$res
## res.x res.y 
##    30    30
cdl_copy$aggregate(factor = c(2, 2), aggtype="sum")  # increase resolution by factor of two
cdl_copy$res
## [1] 60 60

Multiband rasters in velox are pretty straightforwardâ¦ you just load a list of the files (or bands) using the velox() function:

mbr <- velox(list(r1, r2))

Voila, that was your very short introduction to velox. Donât worry, you wonât be graded on this. Itâs just good to know about, since many of you will encounter BIG raster data in your work. You can read more here.
